At the **Edge of the World’s End**, where the sea met the sky in a single, unbroken line, there knelt **Nerissa**, the Keeper of the Tidepool. Her hands were always wet, her fingers tracing the edges of forgotten things—coins, bones, the ink of drowned men’s letters. The ocean did not keep secrets; it only delayed them, and Nerissa was its patient scribe, reading the waves for the stories they carried.

One evening, a scholar named **Elias** washed ashore, his robes heavy with salt, his mind heavy with questions no one could answer. He had sought the truth in every book, every star, but the answers had slipped through his fingers like sand. When he crawled to Nerissa’s feet, his voice was a rasp. *‘Give me the answers,’* he begged. *‘Let the sea tell me what I’ve spent my life chasing.’*

Nerissa did not look up. *‘The tidepool does not give,’* she said. *‘It reveals. And it always returns what it shows—changed.’*

Elias’s fists tightened. *‘Then take something from me in return.’*

Nerissa studied him, then dipped her fingers into the pool, pulling forth a single drop of water, shaping it into a mirror of glass. *‘This will hold the truth—but only until the next wave. And in return, you must give the sea a question.’*

Elias pressed his hand to his chest, where the weight of his unanswered doubts still ached, and let the tide take it. The mirror filled with light, then shattered as the wave receded. Elias emerged from the shallows, his mind silent—but his shadow, when it fell upon the sand, was not his own. It was the shape of his curiosity, endless and shifting, waiting to be filled by those who dared to ask."
